We begin with the line given by the first equation, $y=-\green{3}x-\pink{7}
$. We know the $y$-intercept is $(0,\pink{-7})$, so this is one of our points. Since the slope of the line is $\green{-3}$, we know that another point on the line is $(-1,\pink{-7}+\green{3})$, which is the point $(-1,-4)$.

In a similar manner, we will find that the line given by the second equation passes through $(0,9)$ and $(-1,8)$.
